0159|- [HelpText]
0160|*To make the sucros more general, various enhancements may be added
0161|*by using TUTLOAD and TUTSAVE operations.
0162|*TUTLOAD <sucro file>
S   |         <          >
0163|*loads the sucro program from <sucro file> in the edit field below
S   |                              <          >
0164|*the current line. The printable characters appear in that listing as
0165|*such, but the non-printable characters (like those corresponding to
0166|*various moves of the cursor, RETURN, arrow keys, HOME etc.) are coded
0167|aas special words given in braces. Thus HOME is {home} and RETURN (ENTER)
0168|ais {R}, for example.
0169|*When comparing to the description of the sucro code in the User's Guide
0170|*(1987), the notation style has been completely revised in order to make
0171|*sucro programs more readable. Nothing has been changed in the structure
0172|*and contents of .TUT files of the older Survo versions.
0174|*The code represented in the edit field can be edited freely by using the
0175|*normal editorial functions. After editing, the code is saved back to a
0176|*sucro file by editing TUTLOAD <file> to TUTSAVE <file> and by activating it.
S   |                               <    >            <    >
0177|*When editing sucros, various special codes may be added.
0179|*To spare disk space, related sucros can be saved in one .TUT file.
0180|*Assume that the common file name should be ABCD.TUT . Then any
0181|*sucro, say XYZ, written in the edit field is saved in this file by
0182|*the command TUTSAVE ABCD-XYZ and loaded back to the edit field by the
0183|*command TUTLOAD ABCD-XYZ . It can also be deleted from the file by
0184|*TUTDEL ABCD-XYZ .
0185|*To see the names of sucros saved in ABCD.TUT, use the command
0186|*TUTLOAD ABCD .
0187|*Warning: Never activate TUTSAVE ABCD since it destroys the true contents
0188|*of the ABCD.TUT file.
0190|*Sucros in ABCD.TUT are called by their complete names, i.e. by commands like
0191|*/ABCD-XYZ
0193|- [New]
0194|*Sucros belonging to the same sucro family (file), say ABCD, can call
0195|*each other by commands of the form {load *-PART2} or {call *-PART2}
0196|*where * is now interpreted as ABCD. This makes possible to alter the
0197|*family name (here ABCD) without making any changes in the members.
0198|- [/New]
0200|- [New]
0201|*Instead of loading sucro program text into the edit field, it can be
0202|*written in a text file by the command
0203|*TUTLOAD <sucro_file>,<text_file> .
S   |         <          > <         >
0204|*The current Survo data path is default for the text file.
